<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB3EC070390FA87FC94FAD1" blockId="4.[151,1437,1345,1804]" box="[151,848,1345,1371]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">The seven species placed in this subgenus are listed in table 1.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3446530FFB3EC0703C0FAA2FD39F949" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB3EC0703C0FAA2FDABFA61" blockId="4.[151,1437,1345,1804]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC0703C0FAA2FE86FAF5" bold="true" box="[199,322,1380,1407]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB3EC0702EAFAA3FDB8FAF5" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1981" box="[493,636,1381,1407]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC0702EAFAA3FDB8FAF5" box="[493,636,1381,1407]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Redivivoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises seven species (Table 1). Males are morphologically diverse and no apomorphies are known that distinguish them from those of other subgenera (see detailed discussion in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB3EC070390FA6BFE9AFA42" author="Kuhlmann, M." box="[151,350,1453,1480]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref5829" refString="Kuhlmann, M. (2012 b) Revision of the South African endemic bee genus Redivivoides Michener, 1981 (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Melittidae). European Journal of Taxonomy, 34, 1 - 34. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2012.34" type="journal article" year="2012">Kuhlmann 2012b</bibRefCitation>
). Some can easily be mistaken for males of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB3EC0700DCFA68FBF9FA4D" box="[987,1085,1454,1479]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Deriviva">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC0700DCFA68FBF9FA4D" box="[987,1085,1454,1479]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Deriviva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so they can only be assigned to a subgenus through the associated female.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB3EC0703C0FA33FD39F949" blockId="4.[151,1437,1345,1804]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">
Females lack the broadened hind tibia and basitarsus and the scopa does not consist of densely plumose pubescence for transporting floral oil that females of all other subgenera have. Instead the hind leg is narrow with the hind basitarsus only slightly broadened and the scopa consists of sparse simple bristles (
<figureCitation id="13652A3EFFB3EC070777F9FBFB7BF9DD" box="[1136,1215,1597,1623]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1889,1914]" captionTargetBox="[192,1394,182,1863]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[192,1395,181,1864]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rediviva (Albiviva) albifasciata Whitehead &amp; Steiner ♀: a. metasoma with distinct white apical hair bands. R. (s. str.) whiteheadi Kuhlmann ♀: b. metasoma with indistinct yellowish apical hair bands. R. (Redivivoides) capensis (Kuhlmann) ♀: c. hind leg. R. (Deriviva) intermedia Whitehead &amp; Steiner ♀: d. front leg, coxa with apical hairy spine (s). R. (Deriviva) intermixta Cockerell ♀: e. hind basitarsus with shiny scale-like projection; f. hind leg." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3889569" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3889569/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
) (branched in other subgenera). Within the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB3EC0702E2F9A7FD83F9F1" authorityName="Friese" authorityYear="1911" box="[485,583,1633,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Rediviva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC0702E2F9A7FD83F9F1" box="[485,583,1633,1659]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Rediviva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB3EC0701CCF9A7FC9EF9F1" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1981" box="[715,858,1633,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC0701CCF9A7FC9EF9F1" box="[715,858,1633,1659]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Redivivoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique because they do not collect floral oil for larval nourishment. Detailed descriptions of species including a discussion of morphology and biology were provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB3EC0703F8F96FFE11F94E" author="Kuhlmann, M." box="[255,469,1705,1732]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref5829" refString="Kuhlmann, M. (2012 b) Revision of the South African endemic bee genus Redivivoides Michener, 1981 (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Melittidae). European Journal of Taxonomy, 34, 1 - 34. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2012.34" type="journal article" year="2012">Kuhlmann (2012b)</bibRefCitation>
and are not repeated here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3446530FFB3EC0703C0F90AFEB1F886" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE136BBFFB3EC0703C0F90AFEB1F886" blockId="4.[151,1437,1345,1804]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC0703C0F90AFEA5F96D" bold="true" box="[199,353,1740,1767]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D38FFB3EC07026CF90BFE3EF96D" authorityName="Michener" authorityYear="1981" box="[363,506,1741,1767]" class="Insecta" family="Melittidae" genus="Redivivoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92AEAA9FFB3EC07026CF90BFE3EF96D" box="[363,506,1741,1767]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">Redivivoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are known only from the winter rainfall region of western 
<collectingCountry id="F349762BFFB3EC07060CF90BFA59F96D" box="[1291,1437,1741,1767]" name="South Africa" pageId="4" pageNumber="322">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B4AFFB3EC070398F937FEACF886" author="Kuhlmann, M." box="[159,360,1777,1804]" pageId="4" pageNumber="322" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref5829" refString="Kuhlmann, M. (2012 b) Revision of the South African endemic bee genus Redivivoides Michener, 1981 (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Melittidae). European Journal of Taxonomy, 34, 1 - 34. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2012.34" type="journal article" year="2012">Kuhlmann 2012b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
